# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cpo-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] In mathematics, the phrase **complete partial order** is variously used to refer to at least three similar, but distinct, classes of partially ordered sets, characterized by particular completeness properties.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Complete partial orders play a central role in theoretical computer science: in denotational semantics and domain theory.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] The term **complete partial order**, abbreviated **cpo**, has several possible meanings depending on context.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] A partially ordered set is a **directed-complete partial order** (**dcpo**) if each of its directed subsets has a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] (A subset of a partial order is directed if it is non-empty and every pair of elements has an upper bound in the subset.) In the literature, dcpos sometimes also appear under the label **up-complete poset**.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] A **pointed directed-complete partial order** (**pointed dcpo**, sometimes abbreviated **cppo**), is a dcpo with a least element (usually denoted $\bot$ ).
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Formulated differently, a pointed dcpo has a supremum for every directed *or empty* subset.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] The term **chain-complete partial order** is also used, because of the characterization of pointed dcpos as posets in which every chain has a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] A related notion is that of **ω-complete partial order** (**ω-cpo**).
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] These are posets in which every ω-chain ( $x_{1}\leq x_{2}\leq x_{3}\leq ...$ ) has a supremum that belongs to the poset.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] The same notion can be extended to other cardinalities of chains.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Every dcpo is an ω-cpo, since every ω-chain is a directed set, but the converse is not true.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] However, every ω-cpo with a basis is also a dcpo (with the same basis).
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] An ω-cpo (dcpo) with a basis is also called a **continuous** ω-cpo (or continuous dcpo).
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Note that *complete partial order* is never used to mean a poset in which *all* subsets have suprema; the terminology complete lattice is used for this concept.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Requiring the existence of directed suprema can be motivated by viewing directed sets as generalized approximation sequences and suprema as *limits* of the respective (approximative) computations.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] This intuition, in the context of denotational semantics, was the motivation behind the development of domain theory.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] The dual notion of a directed-complete partial order is called a **filtered-complete partial order**.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] However, this concept occurs far less frequently in practice, since one usually can work on the dual order explicitly.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] By analogy with the Dedekind–MacNeille completion of a partially ordered set, every partially ordered set can be extended uniquely to a minimal dcpo.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] (Markowsky's theorem) An ordered set is a dcpo if and only if it is chain complete; i.e., every non-empty chain has a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] As a corollary, an ordered set is a pointed dcpo if and only if every (possibly empty) chain has a supremum, i.e., if and only if it is chain-complete.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Alternatively, an ordered set P is a pointed dcpo if and only if every order-preserving self-map of P has a least fixpoint.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Note that every continuous function between dcpos is a monotone function.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] This notion of continuity is equivalent to the topological continuity induced by the Scott topology.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] The set of all continuous functions between two dcpos *P* and *Q* is denoted [*P* → *Q*].
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Equipped with the pointwise order, this is again a dcpo, and pointed whenever *Q* is pointed.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Thus the complete partial orders with Scott-continuous maps form a cartesian closed category.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Every order-preserving self-map *f* of a pointed dcpo (*P*, ⊥) has a least fixed-point.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] If *f* is continuous then this fixed-point is equal to the supremum of the iterates (⊥, *f* (⊥), *f* (*f* (⊥)), ...
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] *f* *n*(⊥), ...) of ⊥ (see also the Kleene fixed-point theorem).
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] Another fixed point theorem is the Bourbaki–Witt theorem, stating that if f is a function from a dcpo to itself with the property that $f(x)\geq x$ for all x , then f has a fixed point.
[src:cpo-theory/complete-partial-order] This theorem, in turn, can be used to prove that Zorn's lemma is a consequence of the axiom of choice.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] In mathematics, a **directed set** (or a **directed preorder** or a **filtered set**) is a preordered set in which every finite subset has an upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] In other words, it is a non-empty preordered set A such that for any a and b in A there exists c in A with $a\leq c$ and $b\leq c$ .
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A directed set's preorder is called a **direction**.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] The notion defined above is sometimes called an **upward directed set**.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A **downward directed set** is defined symmetrically, meaning that every finite subset has a lower bound.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Some authors (and this article) assume that a directed set is directed upward, unless otherwise stated.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Other authors call a set directed if and only if it is directed both upward and downward.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Directed sets are a generalization of nonempty totally ordered sets.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] That is, all totally ordered sets are directed sets (contrast *partially* ordered sets, which need not be directed).
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Join-semilattices (which are partially ordered sets) are directed sets as well, but not conversely.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Likewise, lattices are directed sets both upward and downward.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] In topology, directed sets are used to define nets, which generalize sequences and unify the various notions of limit used in analysis.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Directed sets also give rise to direct limits in abstract algebra and (more generally) category theory.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] The set of natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ with the ordinary order $\,\leq \,$ is one of the most important examples of a directed set.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] If an abstract rewriting system $(X,\to )$ is confluent, then its transitive closure $(X,\to ^{*})$ is a directed set.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] If $x_{0}$ is a real number then the set $I:=\mathbb {R} \backslash \lbrace x_{0}\rbrace$ can be turned into a directed set by defining $a\leq _{I}b$ if $\left|a-x_{0}\right|\geq \left|b-x_{0}\right|$ (so "greater" elements are closer to $x_{0}$ ).
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] We then say that the reals have been **directed towards $x_{0}.$** This is an example of a directed set that is *neither* partially ordered nor totally ordered.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Any preordered set with a greatest element is a directed set with the same preorder.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] For instance, in a poset $P,$ every lower closure of an element; that is, every subset of the form $\{a\in P:a\leq x\}$ where x is a fixed element from $P,$ is directed.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A preordered set is directed if and only if the (possibly empty) set of maximal elements is equal to the set of greatest elements.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] The subset inclusion relation $\,\subseteq ,\,$ along with its dual $\,\supseteq ,\,$ define partial orders on any given family of sets.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A non-empty family of sets is a directed set with respect to the partial order $\,\supseteq \,$ (respectively, $\,\subseteq \,$ ) if and only if the intersection (respectively, union) of any two of its members contains as a subset (respectively, is contained as a subset of) some third member.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Many important examples of directed sets can be defined using these partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Let S be a formal theory, which is a set of sentences with certain properties (details of which can be found in the article on the subject).
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] For instance, S could be a first-order theory (like Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory) or a simpler zeroth-order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] The order relation in a directed set is not required to be antisymmetric, and therefore directed sets are not always partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] However, the term *directed set* is also used frequently in the context of posets.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] In this setting, a subset A of a partially ordered set $(P,\leq )$ is called a **directed subset** if it is a directed set according to the same partial order: in other words, it is not the empty set, and every pair of elements has an upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Here the order relation on the elements of A is inherited from P ; for this reason, reflexivity and transitivity need not be required explicitly.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A directed subset of a poset is not required to be downward closed; a subset of a poset is directed if and only if its downward closure is an ideal.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] While the definition of a directed set is for an "upward-directed" set (every pair of elements has an upper bound), it is also possible to define a downward-directed set in which every pair of elements has a common lower bound.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] A subset of a poset is downward-directed if and only if its upper closure is a filter.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] Directed subsets are used in domain theory, which studies directed-complete partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] These are posets in which every upward-directed set is required to have a least upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/directed-set] In this context, directed subsets again provide a generalization of convergent sequences.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Orders are everywhere in mathematics and related fields like computer science.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The first order often discussed in primary school is the standard order on the natural numbers e.g.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] "2 is less than 3", "10 is greater than 5", or "Does Tom have fewer cookies than Sally?".
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This intuitive concept can be extended to orders on other sets of numbers, such as the integers and the reals.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The idea of being greater than or less than another number is one of the basic intuitions of number systems in general (although one usually is also interested in the actual difference of two numbers, which is not given by the order).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Other familiar examples of orderings are the alphabetical order of words in a dictionary and the genealogical property of lineal descent within a group of people.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The notion of order is very general, extending beyond contexts that have an immediate, intuitive feel of sequence or relative quantity.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In other contexts orders may capture notions of containment or specialization.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Some orders, like "less-than" on the natural numbers and alphabetical order on words, have a special property: each element can be *compared* to any other element, i.e. it is smaller (earlier) than, larger (later) than, or identical to.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Consider for example the subset order on a collection of sets: though the set of birds and the set of dogs are both subsets of the set of animals, neither the birds nor the dogs constitutes a subset of the other.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Those orders like the "subset-of" relation which allow *incomparable* elements are called *partial orders*; orders for which every pair of elements is comparable are *total orders*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Order theory captures the intuition of orders that arises from such examples in a general setting.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This is achieved by specifying properties that a relation ≤ must have to be a mathematical order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This more abstract approach makes much sense, because one can derive numerous theorems in the general setting, without focusing on the details of any particular order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] These insights can then be readily transferred to many less abstract applications.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Driven by the wide practical usage of orders, numerous special kinds of ordered sets have been defined, some of which have grown into mathematical fields of their own.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In addition, order theory does not restrict itself to the various classes of ordering relations, but also considers appropriate functions between them.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A simple example of an order theoretic property for functions comes from analysis where monotone functions are frequently found.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The earliest explicit mentionings of partial orders are probably to be found not before the 19th century.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In this context the works of George Boole are of great importance.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Moreover, works of Charles Sanders Peirce, Richard Dedekind, and Ernst Schröder also consider concepts of order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In 1901 Bertrand Russell wrote "On the Notion of Order" exploring the foundations of the idea through generation of series.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] He returned to the topic in part IV of *The Principles of Mathematics* (1903).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The term *poset* as an abbreviation for partially ordered set is attributed to Garrett Birkhoff in the second edition of his influential book *Lattice Theory*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This section introduces ordered sets by building upon the concepts of set theory, arithmetic, and binary relations.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Suppose that *P* is a set and that ≤ is a relation on *P* ('relation *on* a set' is taken to mean 'relation *amongst* its inhabitants', i.e. ≤ is a subset of the cartesian product *P* × *P*).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A set with a partial order on it is called a **partially ordered set**, **poset**, or just **ordered set** if the intended meaning is clear.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] By checking these properties, one immediately sees that the well-known orders on natural numbers, integers, rational numbers and reals are all orders in the above sense.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A partial order with this property is called a total order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] These orders can also be called **linear orders** or **chains**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] While many familiar orders are linear, the subset order on sets provides an example where this is not the case.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Another example is given by the divisibility (or "is-a-factor-of") relation |.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For two natural numbers *n* and *m*, we write *n*|*m* if *n* divides *m* without remainder.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] One easily sees that this yields a partial order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example neither 3 divides 13 nor 13 divides 3, so 3 and 13 are not comparable elements of the divisibility relation on the set of integers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The identity relation = on any set is also a partial order in which every two distinct elements are incomparable.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] It is also the only relation that is both a partial order and an equivalence relation because it satisfies both the antisymmetry property of partial orders and the symmetry property of equivalence relations.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Many advanced properties of posets are interesting mainly for non-linear orders.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Hasse diagrams can visually represent the elements and relations of a partial ordering.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] These are graph drawings where the vertices are the elements of the poset and the ordering relation is indicated by both the edges and the relative positioning of the vertices.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Orders are drawn bottom-up: if an element *x* is smaller than (precedes) *y* then there exists a path from *x* to *y* that is directed upwards.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] It is often necessary for the edges connecting elements to cross each other, but elements must never be located within an edge.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An instructive exercise is to draw the Hasse diagram for the set of natural numbers that are smaller than or equal to 13, ordered by | (the *divides* relation).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Even some infinite sets can be diagrammed by superimposing an ellipsis (...) on a finite sub-order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This works well for the natural numbers, but it fails for the reals, where there is no immediate successor above 0; however, quite often one can obtain an intuition related to diagrams of a similar kind.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In a partially ordered set there may be some elements that play a special role.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The most basic example is given by the **least element** of a poset.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, 1 is the least element of the positive integers and the empty set is the least set under the subset order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The notation 0 is frequently found for the least element, even when no numbers are concerned.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] However, in orders on sets of numbers, this notation might be inappropriate or ambiguous, since the number 0 is not always least.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An example is given by the above divisibility order |, where 1 is the least element since it divides all other numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In contrast, 0 is the number that is divided by all other numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Hence it is the **greatest element** of the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Other frequent terms for the least and greatest elements is **bottom** and **top** or **zero** and **unit**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Least and greatest elements may fail to exist, as the example of the real numbers shows.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] But if they exist, they are always unique.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In contrast, consider the divisibility relation | on the set {2,3,4,5,6}.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Although this set has neither top nor bottom, the elements 2, 3, and 5 have no elements below them, while 4, 5 and 6 have none above.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Such elements are called **minimal** and **maximal**, respectively.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Exchanging ≤ with ≥ yields the definition of maximality.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] As the example shows, there can be many maximal elements and some elements may be both maximal and minimal (e.g.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] However, if there is a least element, then it is the only minimal element of the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Again, in infinite posets maximal elements do not always exist - the set of all *finite* subsets of a given infinite set, ordered by subset inclusion, provides one of many counterexamples.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An important tool to ensure the existence of maximal elements under certain conditions is **Zorn's Lemma**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Subsets of partially ordered sets inherit the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] We already applied this by considering the subset {2,3,4,5,6} of the natural numbers with the induced divisibility ordering.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Now there are also elements of a poset that are special with respect to some subset of the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This leads to the definition of **upper bounds**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Given a subset *S* of some poset *P*, an upper bound of *S* is an element *b* of *P* that is above all elements of *S*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Lower bounds again are defined by inverting the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, −5 is a lower bound of the natural numbers as a subset of the integers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Given a set of sets, an upper bound for these sets under the subset ordering is given by their union.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In fact, this upper bound is quite special: it is the smallest set that contains all of the sets.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Hence, we have found the **least upper bound** of a set of sets.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This concept is also called **supremum** or **join**, and for a set *S* one writes sup(*S*) or $\bigvee S$ for its least upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Conversely, the **greatest lower bound** is known as **infimum** or **meet** and denoted inf(*S*) or $\bigwedge S$ .
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] These concepts play an important role in many applications of order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For two elements *x* and *y*, one also writes $x\vee y$ and $x\wedge y$ for sup({*x*,*y*}) and inf({*x*,*y*}), respectively.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, 1 is the infimum of the positive integers as a subset of integers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For another example, consider again the relation | on natural numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The least upper bound of two numbers is the smallest number that is divided by both of them, i.e. the least common multiple of the numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Greatest lower bounds in turn are given by the greatest common divisor.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In the previous definitions, we often noted that a concept can be defined by just inverting the ordering in a former definition.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This is the case for "least" and "greatest", for "minimal" and "maximal", for "upper bound" and "lower bound", and so on.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This is a general situation in order theory: A given order can be inverted by just exchanging its direction, pictorially flipping the Hasse diagram top-down.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This yields the so-called **dual**, **inverse**, or **opposite order**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Every order theoretic definition has its dual: it is the notion one obtains by applying the definition to the inverse order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Since all concepts are symmetric, this operation preserves the theorems of partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For a given mathematical result, one can just invert the order and replace all definitions by their duals and one obtains another valid theorem.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This is important and useful, since one obtains two theorems for the price of one.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Some more details and examples can be found in the article on duality in order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] There are many ways to construct orders out of given orders.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Another important construction is the cartesian product of two partially ordered sets, taken together with the product order on pairs of elements.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] (Notice carefully that there are three distinct meanings for the relation symbol ≤ in this definition.) The disjoint union of two posets is another typical example of order construction, where the order is just the (disjoint) union of the original orders.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Every partial order ≤ gives rise to a so-called strict order <, by defining *a* < *b* if *a* ≤ *b* and not *b* ≤ *a*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This transformation can be inverted by setting *a* ≤ *b* if *a* < *b* or *a* = *b*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The two concepts are equivalent although in some circumstances one can be more convenient to work with than the other.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] It is reasonable to consider functions between partially ordered sets having certain additional properties that are related to the ordering relations of the two sets.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The most fundamental condition that occurs in this context is monotonicity.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A function *f* from a poset *P* to a poset *Q* is **monotone**, or **order-preserving**, if *a* ≤ *b* in *P* implies *f*(*a*) ≤ *f*(*b*) in *Q* (Noting that, strictly, the two relations here are different since they apply to different sets.).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The converse of this implication leads to functions that are **order-reflecting**, i.e. functions *f* as above for which *f*(*a*) ≤ *f*(*b*) implies *a* ≤ *b*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] On the other hand, a function may also be **order-reversing** or **antitone**, if *a* ≤ *b* implies *f*(*a*) ≥ *f*(*b*).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An **order-embedding** is a function *f* between orders that is both order-preserving and order-reflecting.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Examples for these definitions are found easily.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For instance, the function that maps a natural number to its successor is clearly monotone with respect to the natural order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Any function from a discrete order, i.e. from a set ordered by the identity order "=", is also monotone.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Mapping each natural number to the corresponding real number gives an example for an order embedding.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The set complement on a powerset is an example of an antitone function.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An important question is when two orders are "essentially equal", i.e. when they are the same up to renaming of elements.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] **Order isomorphisms** are functions that define such a renaming.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An order-isomorphism is a monotone bijective function that has a monotone inverse.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This is equivalent to being a surjective order-embedding.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Hence, the image *f*(*P*) of an order-embedding is always isomorphic to *P*, which justifies the term "embedding".
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A more elaborate type of functions is given by so-called **Galois connections**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Monotone Galois connections can be viewed as a generalization of order-isomorphisms, since they constitute of a pair of two functions in converse directions, which are "not quite" inverse to each other, but that still have close relationships.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Another special type of self-maps on a poset are **closure operators**, which are not only monotonic, but also idempotent, i.e.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] These have many applications in all kinds of "closures" that appear in mathematics.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Besides being compatible with the mere order relations, functions between posets may also behave well with respect to special elements and constructions.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, when talking about posets with least element, it may seem reasonable to consider only monotonic functions that preserve this element, i.e. which map least elements to least elements.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] If binary infima ∧ exist, then a reasonable property might be to require that *f*(*x* ∧ *y*) = *f*(*x*) ∧ *f*(*y*), for all *x* and *y*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] All of these properties, and indeed many more, may be compiled under the label of limit-preserving functions.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Finally, one can invert the view, switching from *functions of orders* to *orders of functions*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Indeed, the functions between two posets *P* and *Q* can be ordered via the pointwise order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For two functions *f* and *g*, we have *f* ≤ *g* if *f*(*x*) ≤ *g*(*x*) for all elements *x* of *P*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This occurs for example in domain theory, where function spaces play an important role.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Many of the structures that are studied in order theory employ order relations with further properties.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In fact, even some relations that are not partial orders are of special interest.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Mainly the concept of a preorder has to be mentioned.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A preorder is a relation that is reflexive and transitive, but not necessarily antisymmetric.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Each preorder induces an equivalence relation between elements, where *a* is equivalent to *b*, if *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≤ *a*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Preorders can be turned into orders by identifying all elements that are equivalent with respect to this relation.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Requiring two scores to be separated by a fixed threshold before they may be compared leads to the concept of a semiorder, while allowing the threshold to vary on a per-item basis produces an interval order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Requiring all non-empty subsets to have a minimal element is the defining property of so-called **well-founded orders**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Generalizing well-orders from linear to partial orders, a set is **well partially ordered** if all its non-empty subsets have a finite number of minimal elements.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Many other types of orders arise when the existence of infima and suprema of certain sets is guaranteed.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] However, one can go even further: if all finite non-empty infima exist, then ∧ can be viewed as a total binary operation in the sense of universal algebra.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This condition is called **distributivity** and gives rise to distributive lattices.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] There are some other important distributivity laws which are discussed in the article on distributivity in order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] which both introduce a new operation ~ called **negation**.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Both structures play a role in mathematical logic and especially Boolean algebras have major applications in computer science.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Finally, various structures in mathematics combine orders with even more algebraic operations, as in the case of quantales, that allow for the definition of an addition operation.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Many other important properties of posets exist.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, a poset is **locally finite** if every closed interval [*a*, *b*] in it is finite.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Locally finite posets give rise to incidence algebras which in turn can be used to define the Euler characteristic of finite bounded posets.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In an ordered set, one can define many types of special subsets based on the given order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A simple example are **upper sets**; i.e. sets that contain all elements that are above them in the order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Formally, the **upper closure** of a set *S* in a poset *P* is given by the set {*x* in *P* | there is some *y* in *S* with *y* ≤ *x*}.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A set that is equal to its upper closure is called an upper set.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] More complicated lower subsets are ideals, which have the additional property that each two of their elements have an upper bound within the ideal.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A related concept is that of a directed subset, which like an ideal contains upper bounds of finite subsets, but does not have to be a lower set.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Furthermore, it is often generalized to preordered sets.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A subset which is – as a sub-poset – linearly ordered, is called a chain.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The opposite notion, the antichain, is a subset that contains no two comparable elements; i.e. that is a discrete order.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Although most mathematical areas *use* orders in one or the other way, there are also a few theories that have relationships which go far beyond mere application.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Together with their major points of contact with order theory, some of these are to be presented below.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] As already mentioned, the methods and formalisms of universal algebra are an important tool for many order theoretic considerations.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Beside formalizing orders in terms of algebraic structures that satisfy certain identities, one can also establish other connections to algebra.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] An example is given by the correspondence between Boolean algebras and Boolean rings.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Other issues are concerned with the existence of free constructions, such as free lattices based on a given set of generators.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Furthermore, closure operators are important in the study of universal algebra.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In topology, orders play a very prominent role.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In fact, the collection of open sets provides a classical example of a complete lattice, more precisely a complete Heyting algebra (or "**frame**" or "**locale**").
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Filters and nets are notions closely related to order theory and the closure operator of sets can be used to define a topology.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Beyond these relations, topology can be looked at solely in terms of the open set lattices, which leads to the study of pointless topology.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Furthermore, a natural preorder of elements of the underlying set of a topology is given by the so-called specialization order, that is actually a partial order if the topology is T0.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Conversely, in order theory, one often makes use of topological results.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] There are various ways to define subsets of an order which can be considered as open sets of a topology.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Considering topologies on a poset (*X*, ≤) that in turn induce ≤ as their specialization order, the finest such topology is the Alexandrov topology, given by taking all upper sets as opens.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Conversely, the coarsest topology that induces the specialization order is the upper topology, having the complements of principal ideals (i.e. sets of the form {*y* in *X* | *y* ≤ *x*} for some *x*) as a subbase.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Additionally, a topology with specialization order ≤ may be order consistent, meaning that their open sets are "inaccessible by directed suprema" (with respect to ≤).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The finest order consistent topology is the Scott topology, which is coarser than the Alexandrov topology.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] A third important topology in this spirit is the Lawson topology.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] There are close connections between these topologies and the concepts of order theory.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, a function preserves directed suprema if and only if it is continuous with respect to the Scott topology (for this reason this order theoretic property is also called Scott-continuity).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] The visualization of orders with Hasse diagrams has a straightforward generalization: instead of displaying lesser elements *below* greater ones, the direction of the order can also be depicted by giving directions to the edges of a graph.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] In this way, each order is seen to be equivalent to a directed acyclic graph, where the nodes are the elements of the poset and there is a directed path from *a* to *b* if and only if *a* ≤ *b*.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Dropping the requirement of being acyclic, one can also obtain all preorders.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] When equipped with all transitive edges, these graphs in turn are just special categories, where elements are objects and each set of morphisms between two elements is at most singleton.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Functions between orders become functors between categories.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Many ideas of order theory are just concepts of category theory in small.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] For example, an infimum is just a categorical product.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] More generally, one can capture infima and suprema under the abstract notion of a categorical limit (or *colimit*, respectively).
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Another place where categorical ideas occur is the concept of a (monotone) Galois connection, which is just the same as a pair of adjoint functors.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] But category theory also has its impact on order theory on a larger scale.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Classes of posets with appropriate functions as discussed above form interesting categories.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Often one can also state constructions of orders, like the product order, in terms of categories.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] Further insights result when categories of orders are found categorically equivalent to other categories, for example of topological spaces.
[src:cpo-theory/order-theory] This line of research leads to various *representation theorems*, often collected under the label of Stone duality.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In mathematics, especially order theory, a **partial order** on a set is an arrangement such that, for certain pairs of elements, one precedes the other.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The word *partial* is used to indicate that not every pair of elements needs to be comparable; that is, there may be pairs for which neither element precedes the other.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Partial orders thus generalize total orders, in which every pair is comparable.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Formally, a partial order is a homogeneous binary relation that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A **partially ordered set** (**poset** for short) is an ordered pair $P=(X,\leq )$ consisting of a set X (called the *ground set* of P ) and a partial order $\leq$ on X .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] When the meaning is clear from context and there is no ambiguity about the partial order, the set X itself is sometimes called a poset.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The term *partial order* usually refers to the reflexive partial order relations, referred to in this article as *non-strict* partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] However some authors use the term for the other common type of partial order relations, the irreflexive partial order relations, also called strict partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Strict and non-strict partial orders can be put into a one-to-one correspondence, so for every strict partial order there is a unique corresponding non-strict partial order, and vice versa.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A **reflexive**, **weak**, or **non-strict partial order**, commonly referred to simply as a **partial order**, is a homogeneous relation ≤ on a set P that is reflexive, antisymmetric, and transitive.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Antisymmetry: if $a\leq b$ and $b\leq a$ then $a=b$ , i.e. no two distinct elements precede each other.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Transitivity: if $a\leq b$ and $b\leq c$ then $a\leq c$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A non-strict partial order is also known as an antisymmetric preorder.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Transitivity: if $a<b$ and $b<c$ then $a<c$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A transitive relation is asymmetric if and only if it is irreflexive.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] So the definition is the same if it omits either irreflexivity or asymmetry (but not both).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A strict partial order is also known as a strict preorder.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Strict and non-strict partial orders on a set P are closely related.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Conversely, a strict partial order < on P may be converted to a non-strict partial order by adjoining all relationships of that form; that is, $\leq \;:=\;\Delta _{P}\;\cup \;<\;$ is a non-strict partial order.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The *dual* (or *opposite*) $R^{\text{op}}$ of a partial order relation R is defined by letting $R^{\text{op}}$ be the converse relation of R , i.e. $xR^{\text{op}}y$ if and only if $yRx$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The dual of a non-strict partial order is a non-strict partial order, and the dual of a strict partial order is a strict partial order.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The dual of a dual of a relation is the original relation.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Strictly speaking, the term *partially ordered set* refers to a set with all of these relations defined appropriately.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] But practically, one need only consider a single relation, $(P,\leq )$ or $(P,<)$ , or, in rare instances, the non-strict and strict relations together, $(P,\leq ,<)$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The term *ordered set* is sometimes used as a shorthand for *partially ordered set*, as long as it is clear from the context that no other kind of order is meant.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In particular, totally ordered sets can also be referred to as "ordered sets", especially in areas where these structures are more common than posets.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Some authors use different symbols than $\leq$ such as $\sqsubseteq$ or $\preceq$ to distinguish partial orders from total orders.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] When referring to partial orders, $\leq$ should not be taken as the complement of > .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The relation > is the converse of the irreflexive kernel of $\leq$ , which is always a subset of the complement of $\leq$ , but > is equal to the complement of $\leq$ if, and only if, $\leq$ is a total order.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Another way of defining a partial order, found in computer science, is via a notion of comparison.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Specifically, given $\leq ,<,\geq ,{\text{ and }}>$ as defined previously, it can be observed that two elements *x* and *y* may stand in any of four mutually exclusive relationships to each other: either *x* < *y*, or *x* = *y*, or *x* > *y*, or *x* and *y* are *incomparable*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This can be represented by a function ${\text{compare}}:P\times P\to \{<,>,=,\vert \}$ that returns one of four codes when given two elements.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This definition is equivalent to a *partial order on a setoid*, where equality is taken to be a defined equivalence relation rather than set equality.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Wallis defines a more general notion of a *partial order relation* as any homogeneous relation that is transitive and antisymmetric.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This includes both reflexive and irreflexive partial orders as subtypes.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A finite poset can be visualized through its Hasse diagram.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Specifically, taking a strict partial order relation $(P,<)$ , a directed acyclic graph (DAG) may be constructed by taking each element of P to be a node and each element of < to be an edge.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The transitive reduction of this DAG is then the Hasse diagram.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Similarly this process can be reversed to construct strict partial orders from certain DAGs.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In contrast, the graph associated to a non-strict partial order has self-loops at every node and therefore is not a DAG; when a non-strict order is said to be depicted by a Hasse diagram, actually the corresponding strict order is shown.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] One familiar example of a partially ordered set is a collection of people ordered by genealogical descendancy.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Some pairs of people bear the descendant-ancestor relationship, but other pairs of people are incomparable, with neither being a descendant of the other.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] are highlighted in green and red, respectively.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In order of increasing strength, i.e., decreasing sets of pairs, three of the possible partial orders on the Cartesian product of two partially ordered sets are (see Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] All three can similarly be defined for the Cartesian product of more than two sets.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Applied to ordered vector spaces over the same field, the result is in each case also an ordered vector space.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] See also orders on the Cartesian product of totally ordered sets.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If two posets are well-ordered, then so is their ordinal sum.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Series-parallel partial orders are formed from the ordinal sum operation (in this context called series composition) and another operation called parallel composition.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Parallel composition is the disjoint union of two partially ordered sets, with no order relation between elements of one set and elements of the other set.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The examples use the poset $({\mathcal {P}}(\{x,y,z\}),\subseteq )$ consisting of the set of all subsets of a three-element set $\{x,y,z\},$ ordered by set inclusion (see Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] As another example, consider the positive integers, ordered by divisibility: 1 is a least element, as it divides all other elements; on the other hand this poset does not have a greatest element.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This partially ordered set does not even have any maximal elements, since any *g* divides for instance 2*g*, which is distinct from it, so *g* is not maximal.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If the number 1 is excluded, while keeping divisibility as ordering on the elements greater than 1, then the resulting poset does not have a least element, but any prime number is a minimal element for it.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In this poset, 60 is an upper bound (though not a least upper bound) of the subset $\{2,3,5,10\},$ which does not have any lower bound (since 1 is not in the poset); on the other hand 2 is a lower bound of the subset of powers of 2, which does not have any upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If the number 0 is included, this will be the greatest element, since this is a multiple of every integer (see Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Given two partially ordered sets (*S*, ≤) and (*T*, ≼), a function $f:S\to T$ is called **order-preserving**, or **monotone**, or **isotone**, if for all $x,y\in S,$ $x\leq y$ implies *f*(*x*) ≼ *f*(*y*).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If (*U*, ≲) is also a partially ordered set, and both $f:S\to T$ and $g:T\to U$ are order-preserving, their composition $g\circ f:S\to U$ is order-preserving, too.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A function $f:S\to T$ is called **order-reflecting** if for all $x,y\in S,$ *f*(*x*) ≼ *f*(*y*) implies $x\leq y.$ If f is both order-preserving and order-reflecting, then it is called an **order-embedding** of (*S*, ≤) into (*T*, ≼).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In the latter case, f is necessarily injective, since $f(x)=f(y)$ implies $x\leq y{\text{ and }}y\leq x$ and in turn $x=y$ according to the antisymmetry of $\leq .$ If an order-embedding between two posets *S* and *T* exists, one says that *S* can be **embedded** into *T*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If an order-embedding $f:S\to T$ is bijective, it is called an **order isomorphism**, and the partial orders (*S*, ≤) and (*T*, ≼) are said to be **isomorphic**.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Isomorphic orders have structurally similar Hasse diagrams (see Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] It can be shown that if order-preserving maps $f:S\to T$ and $g:T\to U$ exist such that $g\circ f$ and $f\circ g$ yields the identity function on *S* and *T*, respectively, then *S* and *T* are order-isomorphic.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] For example, a mapping $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {P} (\mathbb {N} )$ from the set of natural numbers (ordered by divisibility) to the power set of natural numbers (ordered by set inclusion) can be defined by taking each number to the set of its prime divisors.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] It is order-preserving: if x divides y, then each prime divisor of x is also a prime divisor of y.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] However, it is neither injective (since it maps both 12 and 6 to $\{2,3\}$ ) nor order-reflecting (since 12 does not divide 6).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Taking instead each number to the set of its prime power divisors defines a map $g:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {P} (\mathbb {N} )$ that is order-preserving, order-reflecting, and hence an order-embedding.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] It is not an order-isomorphism (since it, for instance, does not map any number to the set $\{4\}$ ), but it can be made one by restricting its codomain to $g(\mathbb {N} ).$ Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] 7b shows a subset of $\mathbb {N}$ and its isomorphic image under g.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The construction of such an order-isomorphism into a power set can be generalized to a wide class of partial orders, called distributive lattices; see *Birkhoff's representation theorem*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Note that *S*(*n*, *k*) refers to Stirling numbers of the second kind.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The number of strict partial orders is the same as that of partial orders.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If the count is made only up to isomorphism, the sequence 1, 1, 2, 5, 16, 63, 318, ...
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] (sequence A000112 in the OEIS) is obtained.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A poset $P^{*}=(X^{*},\leq ^{*})$ is called a **subposet** of another poset $P=(X,\leq )$ provided that $X^{*}$ is a subset of X and $\leq ^{*}$ is a subset of $\leq$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The latter condition is equivalent to the requirement that for any x and y in $X^{*}$ (and thus also in X ), if $x\leq ^{*}y$ then $x\leq y$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] If $P^{*}$ is a subposet of P and furthermore, for all x and y in $X^{*}$ , whenever $x\leq y$ we also have $x\leq ^{*}y$ , then we call $P^{*}$ the subposet of P **induced** by $X^{*}$ , and write $P^{*}=P[X^{*}]$ .
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A partial order $\leq ^{*}$ on a set X is called an **extension** of another partial order $\leq$ on X provided that for all elements $x,y\in X,$ whenever $x\leq y,$ it is also the case that $x\leq ^{*}y.$ A linear extension is an extension that is also a linear (that is, total) order.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] As a classic example, the lexicographic order of totally ordered sets is a linear extension of their product order.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Every partial order can be extended to a total order (order-extension principle).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In computer science, algorithms for finding linear extensions of partial orders (represented as the reachability orders of directed acyclic graphs) are called topological sorting.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Posets are equivalent to one another if and only if they are isomorphic.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] In a poset, the smallest element, if it exists, is an initial object, and the largest element, if it exists, is a terminal object.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Also, every preordered set is equivalent to a poset.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Finally, every subcategory of a poset is isomorphism-closed.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A **convex set** in a poset *P* is a subset I of *P* with the property that, for any *x* and *y* in I and any *z* in *P*, if *x* ≤ *z* ≤ *y*, then *z* is also in I.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This definition generalizes the definition of intervals of real numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] When there is possible confusion with convex sets of geometry, one uses **order-convex** instead of "convex".
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A **convex sublattice** of a lattice *L* is a sublattice of *L* that is also a convex set of *L*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Every nonempty convex sublattice can be uniquely represented as the intersection of a filter and an ideal of *L*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Whenever *a* ≤ *b* does not hold, all these intervals are empty.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Every interval is a convex set, but the converse does not hold; for example, in the poset of divisors of 120, ordered by divisibility (see Fig.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] 7b), the set {1, 2, 4, 5, 8} is convex, but not an interval.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] An interval I is bounded if there exist elements $a,b\in P$ such that *I* ⊆ [*a*, *b*].
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] Every interval that can be represented in interval notation is obviously bounded, but the converse is not true.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] For example, let *P* = (0, 1) ∪ (1, 2) ∪ (2, 3) as a subposet of the real numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The subset (1, 2) is a bounded interval, but it has no infimum or supremum in *P*, so it cannot be written in interval notation using elements of *P*.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] A poset is called locally finite if every bounded interval is finite.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] For example, the integers are locally finite under their natural ordering.
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] The lexicographical order on the cartesian product $\mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N}$ is not locally finite, since (1, 2) ≤ (1, 3) ≤ (1, 4) ≤ (1, 5) ≤ ... ≤ (2, 1).
[src:cpo-theory/partially-ordered-set] This concept of an interval in a partial order should not be confused with the particular class of partial orders known as the interval orders.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In mathematics, a **join-semilattice** (or **upper semilattice**) is a partially ordered set that has a join (a least upper bound) for any nonempty finite subset.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Dually, a **meet-semilattice** (or **lower semilattice**) is a partially ordered set which has a meet (or greatest lower bound) for any nonempty finite subset.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Every join-semilattice is a meet-semilattice in the inverse order and vice versa.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A lattice is a partially ordered set that is both a meet- and join-semilattice with respect to the same partial order.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Algebraically, a lattice is a set with two associative, commutative, idempotent binary operations linked by corresponding absorption laws.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The greatest lower bound of the set {*x*, *y*} is called the meet of *x* and *y*, denoted *x* ∧ *y*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Replacing "greatest lower bound" with "least upper bound" results in the dual concept of a *join-semilattice*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The least upper bound of {*x*, *y*} is called the join of *x* and *y*, denoted *x* ∨ *y*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Meet and join are binary operations on *S*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A simple induction argument shows that the existence of all possible pairwise suprema (infima), as per the definition, implies the existence of all non-empty finite suprema (infima).
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A join-semilattice is **bounded** if it has a least element, the join of the empty set.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Dually, a meet-semilattice is **bounded** if it has a greatest element, the meet of the empty set.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Other properties may be assumed; see the article on completeness in order theory for more discussion on this subject.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] That article also discusses how we may rephrase the above definition in terms of the existence of suitable Galois connections between related posets—an approach of special interest for category theoretic investigations of the concept.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A meet-semilattice $\langle S,\land \rangle$ is **bounded** if *S* includes an identity element 1 such that *x* ∧ 1 = *x* for all *x* in *S*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] If the symbol ∨, called **join**, replaces ∧ in the definition just given, the structure is called a *join-semilattice*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] One can be ambivalent about the particular choice of symbol for the operation, and speak simply of *semilattices*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A semilattice is a commutative, idempotent semigroup; i.e., a commutative band.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A bounded semilattice is an idempotent commutative monoid.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A partial order is induced on a meet-semilattice by setting *x* ≤ *y* whenever *x* ∧ *y* = *x*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] For a join-semilattice, the order is induced by setting *x* ≤ *y* whenever *x* ∨ *y* = *y*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In a bounded meet-semilattice, the identity 1 is the greatest element of *S*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Similarly, an identity element in a join semilattice is a least element.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] An order theoretic meet-semilattice ⟨*S*, ≤⟩ gives rise to a binary operation ∧ such that ⟨*S*, ∧⟩ is an algebraic meet-semilattice.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Conversely, the meet-semilattice ⟨*S*, ∧⟩ gives rise to a binary relation ≤ that partially orders *S* in the following way: for all elements *x* and *y* in *S*, *x* ≤ *y* if and only if *x* = *x* ∧ *y*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The relation ≤ introduced in this way defines a partial ordering from which the binary operation ∧ may be recovered.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Conversely, the order induced by the algebraically defined semilattice ⟨*S*, ∧⟩ coincides with that induced by ≤.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Hence the two definitions may be used interchangeably, depending on which one is more convenient for a particular purpose.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A similar conclusion holds for join-semilattices and the dual ordering ≥.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Semilattices are employed to construct other order structures, or in conjunction with other completeness properties.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] because a set is not a member of itself.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The above algebraic definition of a semilattice suggests a notion of morphism between two semilattices.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Hence *f* is just a homomorphism of the two semigroups associated with each semilattice.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In the order-theoretic formulation, these conditions just state that a homomorphism of join-semilattices is a function that preserves binary joins and least elements, if such there be.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The obvious dual—replacing ∧ with ∨ and 0 with 1—transforms this definition of a join-semilattice homomorphism into its meet-semilattice equivalent.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Any semilattice homomorphism is necessarily monotone with respect to the associated ordering relation.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] There is a well-known equivalence between the category ${\mathcal {S}}$ of join-semilattices with zero with $(\vee ,0)$ -homomorphisms and the category ${\mathcal {A}}$ of algebraic lattices with compactness-preserving complete join-homomorphisms, as follows.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] With a join-semilattice S with zero, we associate its ideal lattice $\operatorname {Id} \ S$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] With a $(\vee ,0)$ -homomorphism $f\colon S\to T$ of $(\vee ,0)$ -semilattices, we associate the map $\operatorname {Id} \ f\colon \operatorname {Id} \ S\to \operatorname {Id} \ T$ , that with any ideal I of S associates the ideal of T generated by $f(I)$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This defines a functor $\operatorname {Id} \colon {\mathcal {S}}\to {\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Conversely, with every algebraic lattice A we associate the $(\vee ,0)$ -semilattice $K(A)$ of all compact elements of A , and with every compactness-preserving complete join-homomorphism $f\colon A\to B$ between algebraic lattices we associate the restriction $K(f)\colon K(A)\to K(B)$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This defines a functor $K\colon {\mathcal {A}}\to {\mathcal {S}}$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The pair $(\operatorname {Id} ,K)$ defines a category equivalence between ${\mathcal {S}}$ and ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Surprisingly, there is a notion of "distributivity" applicable to semilattices, even though distributivity conventionally requires the interaction of two binary operations.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This notion requires but a single operation, and generalizes the distributivity condition for lattices.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Distributive meet-semilattices are defined dually.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] These definitions are justified by the fact that any distributive join-semilattice in which binary meets exist is a distributive lattice.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] See the entry distributivity (order theory).
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A join-semilattice is distributive if and only if the lattice of its ideals (under inclusion) is distributive.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Nowadays, the term "complete semilattice" has no generally accepted meaning, and various mutually inconsistent definitions exist.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] If completeness is taken to require the existence of all infinite joins, or all infinite meets, whichever the case may be, as well as finite ones, this immediately leads to partial orders that are in fact complete lattices.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] For why the existence of all possible infinite joins entails the existence of all possible infinite meets (and vice versa), see the entry completeness (order theory).
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Nevertheless, the literature on occasion still takes complete join- or meet-semilattices to be complete lattices.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In this case, "completeness" denotes a restriction on the scope of the homomorphisms.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Specifically, a complete join-semilattice requires that the homomorphisms preserve all joins, but contrary to the situation we find for completeness properties, this does not require that homomorphisms preserve all meets.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] On the other hand, we can conclude that every such mapping is the lower adjoint of some Galois connection.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The corresponding (unique) upper adjoint will then be a homomorphism of complete meet-semilattices.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This gives rise to a number of useful categorical dualities between the categories of all complete semilattices with morphisms preserving all meets or joins, respectively.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Another usage of "complete meet-semilattice" refers to a bounded complete cpo.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] A complete meet-semilattice in this sense is arguably the "most complete" meet-semilattice that is not necessarily a complete lattice.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Indeed, a complete meet-semilattice has all *non-empty* meets (which is equivalent to being bounded complete) and all directed joins.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] If such a structure has also a greatest element (the meet of the empty set), it is also a complete lattice.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Thus a complete semilattice turns out to be "a complete lattice possibly lacking a top".
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This definition is of interest specifically in domain theory, where bounded complete algebraic cpos are studied as Scott domains.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Hence Scott domains have been called *algebraic semilattices*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Cardinality-restricted notions of completeness for semilattices have been rarely considered in the literature.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] This section presupposes some knowledge of category theory.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In various situations, free semilattices exist.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] For example, the forgetful functor from the category of join-semilattices (and their homomorphisms) to the category of sets (and functions) admits a left adjoint.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Therefore, the free join-semilattice **F**(*S*) over a set *S* is constructed by taking the collection of all non-empty *finite* subsets of *S*, ordered by subset inclusion.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Clearly, *S* can be embedded into **F**(*S*) by a mapping *e* that takes any element *s* in *S* to the singleton set {*s*}.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Then any function *f* from a *S* to a join-semilattice *T* (more formally, to the underlying set of *T*) induces a unique homomorphism *f'* between the join-semilattices **F**(*S*) and *T*, such that *f* = *f'* ○ *e*.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Explicitly, *f'* is given by ${\textstyle f'(A)=\bigvee \{f(s)|s\in A\}.}$ Now the obvious uniqueness of *f'* suffices to obtain the required adjunction—the morphism-part of the functor **F** can be derived from general considerations (see adjoint functors).
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] The case of free meet-semilattices is dual, using the opposite subset inclusion as an ordering.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] For join-semilattices with bottom, we just add the empty set to the above collection of subsets.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] In addition, semilattices often serve as generators for free objects within other categories.
[src:cpo-theory/semilattice] Notably, both the forgetful functors from the category of frames and frame-homomorphisms, and from the category of distributive lattices and lattice-homomorphisms, have a left adjoint.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] In mathematics, the **infimum** (abbreviated **inf**; pl.: **infima**) of a subset S of a partially ordered set P is the greatest element in P that is less than or equal to each element of $S,$ if such an element exists.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If the infimum of S exists, it is unique, and if *b* is a lower bound of S , then *b* is less than or equal to the infimum of S .
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Consequently, the term *greatest lower bound* (abbreviated as *GLB*) is also commonly used.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The **supremum** (abbreviated **sup**; pl.: **suprema**) of a subset S of a partially ordered set P is the least element in P that is greater than or equal to each element of $S,$ if such an element exists.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If the supremum of S exists, it is unique, and if *b* is an upper bound of S , then the supremum of S is less than or equal to *b*.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Consequently, the supremum is also referred to as the *least upper bound* (or *LUB*).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The infimum is, in a precise sense, dual to the concept of a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Infima and suprema of real numbers are common special cases that are important in analysis, and especially in Lebesgue integration.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] However, the general definitions remain valid in the more abstract setting of order theory where arbitrary partially ordered sets are considered.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The concepts of infimum and supremum are close to minimum and maximum, but are more useful in analysis because they better characterize special sets which may have *no minimum or maximum*.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] An infimum of a set is always and only defined relative to a superset of the set in question.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For example, there is no infimum of the positive real numbers inside the positive real numbers (as their own superset), nor any infimum of the positive real numbers inside the complex numbers with positive real part.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] We can also define suprema and infima without restricting to sets.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For example, there is no set containing all cardinal numbers (and there is no greatest cardinal number), but the axiom of choice implies that every set of cardinal numbers has a least upper bound among cardinal numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The axiom of choice is equivalent to the statement that every nonempty set of cardinal numbers has a minimum element (which is also the infimum of the set).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The empty set of cardinal numbers has many lower bounds but no greatest lower bound among cardinal numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Infima and suprema do not necessarily exist.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Existence of an infimum of a subset S of P can fail if S has no lower bound at all, or if the set of lower bounds does not contain a greatest element.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Consequently, partially ordered sets for which certain infima are known to exist become especially interesting.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For instance, a lattice is a partially ordered set in which all *nonempty finite* subsets have both a supremum and an infimum, and a complete lattice is a partially ordered set in which *all* subsets have both a supremum and an infimum.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] More information on the various classes of partially ordered sets that arise from such considerations are found in the article on completeness properties.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If the supremum of a subset S exists, it is unique.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If S contains a greatest element, then that element is the supremum; otherwise, the supremum does not belong to S (or does not exist).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Likewise, if the infimum exists, it is unique.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If S contains a least element, then that element is the infimum; otherwise, the infimum does not belong to S (or does not exist).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For example, consider the set of negative real numbers (excluding zero).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] This set has no greatest element, since for every element of the set, there is another, larger, element.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For instance, for any negative real number $x,$ there is another negative real number ${\tfrac {x}{2}},$ which is greater.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] On the other hand, every real number greater than or equal to zero is certainly an upper bound on this set.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Hence, 0 is the least upper bound of the negative reals, so the supremum is 0.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] This set has a supremum but no greatest element.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] However, the definition of maximal and minimal elements is more general.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] In particular, a set can have many maximal and minimal elements, whereas infima and suprema are unique.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Whereas maxima and minima must be members of the subset that is under consideration, the infimum and supremum of a subset need not be members of that subset themselves.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Finally, a partially ordered set may have many minimal upper bounds without having a least upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Minimal upper bounds are those upper bounds for which there is no strictly smaller element that also is an upper bound.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] This does not say that each minimal upper bound is smaller than all other upper bounds, it merely is not greater.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The distinction between "minimal" and "least" is only possible when the given order is not a total one.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] In a totally ordered set, like the real numbers, the concepts are the same.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] As an example, let S be the set of all finite subsets of natural numbers and consider the partially ordered set obtained by taking all sets from S together with the set of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ and the set of positive real numbers $\mathbb {R} ^{+},$ ordered by subset inclusion as above.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Then clearly both $\mathbb {Z}$ and $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ are greater than all finite sets of natural numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Yet, neither is $\mathbb {R} ^{+}$ smaller than $\mathbb {Z}$ nor is the converse true: both sets are minimal upper bounds but none is a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The *least-upper-bound property* is an example of the aforementioned completeness properties which is typical for the set of real numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] This property is sometimes called *Dedekind completeness*.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] If an ordered set S has the property that every nonempty subset of S having an upper bound also has a least upper bound, then S is said to have the least-upper-bound property.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] As noted above, the set $\mathbb {R}$ of all real numbers has the least-upper-bound property.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] An example of a set that *lacks* the least-upper-bound property is $\mathbb {Q} ,$ the set of rational numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Another example is the hyperreals; there is no least upper bound of the set of positive infinitesimals.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The least-upper-bound property is an indicator of the suprema.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] In analysis, infima and suprema of subsets S of the real numbers are particularly important.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] For instance, the negative real numbers do not have a greatest element, and their supremum is 0 (which is not a negative real number).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The completeness of the real numbers implies (and is equivalent to) that any bounded nonempty subset S of the real numbers has an infimum and a supremum.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Expressing the infimum and supremum as a limit of a such a sequence allows theorems from various branches of mathematics to be applied.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Although this discussion focused on $\sup ,$ similar conclusions can be reached for $\inf$ with appropriate changes (such as requiring that f be non-increasing rather than non-decreasing).
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Other norms defined in terms of $\sup$ or $\inf$ include the weak $L^{p,w}$ space norms (for $1\leq p<\infty$ ), the norm on Lebesgue space $L^{\infty }(\Omega ,\mu ),$ and operator norms.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Monotone sequences in S that converge to $\sup S$ (or to $\inf S$ ) can also be used to help prove many of the formula given below, since addition and multiplication of real numbers are continuous operations.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The following formulas depend on a notation that conveniently generalizes arithmetic operations on sets.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] Throughout, $A,B\subseteq \mathbb {R}$ are sets of real numbers.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The Minkowski sum of two sets A and B of real numbers is the set $A+B~:=~\{a+b:a\in A,b\in B\}$ consisting of all possible arithmetic sums of pairs of numbers, one from each set.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] In the last example, the supremum of a set of rationals is irrational, which means that the rationals are incomplete.
[src:cpo-theory/supremum] The supremum of a set S containing subsets of some set X is the union of the subsets when considering the partially ordered set $(P(X),\subseteq )$ , where P is the power set of X and $\,\subseteq \,$ is subset.
